<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1352,2028]" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,463,1641,1667]" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">External morphology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[473,688,1642,1667]" class="Demospongiae" family="Acarnidae" genus="Iophon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="22" pageNumber="483" phylum="Porifera" rank="subSpecies" species="situ" subSpecies="appearance">
<emphasis box="[473,688,1642,1667]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">In situ appearance</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[706,874,1641,1668]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1415,1440]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,661,1395]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,661,1395]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 11. Phorbas glaberrimus (Topsent, 1917). A. In situ appearance BELUM.Mc2015.698. B. In situ appearance, close up of sponge surface, BELUM.Mc2015.698. C. Skeleton BELUM.Mc2015.664, scale bar 1000 µm. D. Spicules BELUM. Mc2015.698, scale bar 200 µm. E. Chelae BELUM.Mc2015.698, scale bar 10µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376052/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">Figure 11A, B</figureCitation>
): Very large thickly encrusting specimens, some over 
<quantity box="[208,277,1677,1704]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="483" unit="cm" value="30.0">30 cm</quantity>
in diameter and over 
<quantity box="[521,590,1676,1704]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="22" pageNumber="483" unit="cm" value="15.0">15 cm</quantity>
thick. The sponge is cream but the surface layer is often brown (potentially from algae) so the densely packed pore sieves, which remain cream, are very distinct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1352,2028]" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">
<emphasis box="[199,459,1749,1775]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">Preserved appearance.</emphasis>
Firm, grey, mass. Skeletal columns clearly distinguishable and spaces visible between them.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1352,2028]" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,1820,1847]" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">Skeleton</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[315,443,1821,1847]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1415,1440]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,661,1395]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,661,1395]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 11. Phorbas glaberrimus (Topsent, 1917). A. In situ appearance BELUM.Mc2015.698. B. In situ appearance, close up of sponge surface, BELUM.Mc2015.698. C. Skeleton BELUM.Mc2015.664, scale bar 1000 µm. D. Spicules BELUM. Mc2015.698, scale bar 200 µm. E. Chelae BELUM.Mc2015.698, scale bar 10µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376052/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">Figure 11C</figureCitation>
): Choanosomal skeleton composed of a basal layer of acanthostyles from which thick ascending columns of up to 20 oxea ascend. Acanthostyles echinate the lower parts of these columns. In the ectosome the ends of the columns of oxea fan out to form a continuous surface layer. Chelae are very abundant and scattered throughout tissue.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1352,2028]" box="[199,800,1964,1992]" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,307,1964,1991]" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">Spicules:</emphasis>
Measurements from 
<collectionCode box="[545,645,1964,1991]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/2x42-q9ch" name="Ulster Museum, Belfast" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">BELUM</collectionCode>
.Mc2015.698.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1352,2028]" box="[199,1106,2000,2028]" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">
Oxeas (
<figureCitation box="[284,417,2001,2027]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1415,1440]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,661,1395]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,661,1395]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 11. Phorbas glaberrimus (Topsent, 1917). A. In situ appearance BELUM.Mc2015.698. B. In situ appearance, close up of sponge surface, BELUM.Mc2015.698. C. Skeleton BELUM.Mc2015.664, scale bar 1000 µm. D. Spicules BELUM. Mc2015.698, scale bar 200 µm. E. Chelae BELUM.Mc2015.698, scale bar 10µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376052/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="483">Figure 11D</figureCitation>
): 429(484)528 by 12(15) 
<quantity box="[695,774,2000,2028]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="483" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 µm</quantity>
. Fusiform with abrupt points.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,153,647]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">
Acanthostyles: 202(268)403 by 14(20) 
<quantity box="[640,719,153,179]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" unit="mm" value="27.0">27 µm</quantity>
. Parallel sided with an abrupt point. Head not tylote. Strongly spined along whole length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,153,647]" box="[199,596,225,251]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">
Chelae (
<figureCitation box="[291,422,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1415,1440]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,661,1395]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,661,1395]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 11. Phorbas glaberrimus (Topsent, 1917). A. In situ appearance BELUM.Mc2015.698. B. In situ appearance, close up of sponge surface, BELUM.Mc2015.698. C. Skeleton BELUM.Mc2015.664, scale bar 1000 µm. D. Spicules BELUM. Mc2015.698, scale bar 200 µm. E. Chelae BELUM.Mc2015.698, scale bar 10µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376052/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">Figure 11E</figureCitation>
): 22(24) 
<quantity box="[516,592,225,251]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" unit="mm" value="28.0">28 µm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,153,647]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,261,287]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Topsent, 1917)" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1917" baseAuthorityName="Topsent" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[322,745,261,287]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymedesmiidae" genus="Phorbas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="glaberrimus">
<emphasis box="[322,561,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">Phorbas glaberrimus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Topsent, E." box="[576,737,261,287]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref37835" refString="Topsent, E. (1917) Spongiaires. In: Joubin, L. (Ed.), Deuxieme Expedition Antarctique Francaise (1908 - 1910) Commandee par le Dr. Jean Charcot. Sciences Physiques: Documents Scientifiques. Masson &amp; Cie, Paris, pp. 1 - 88." type="book chapter" year="1917">Topsent, 1917</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
was originally described from 
<quantity box="[1095,1166,261,287]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9699999999999998" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" unit="m" value="297.0">297 m</quantity>
in the Antarctic and ap- pears to be a good match for these specimens, although Topsent reports slightly larger oxeas (530–600 by 20–22 μm). 
<bibRefCitation author="Rios, P." box="[213,348,333,360]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" refId="ref36627" refString="Rios, P. (2006) Esponjas del orden Poecilosclerida de las campanas espanolas de bentos Antartico. Unpublished PhD Thesis, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, 527 pp." type="book" year="2006">Rios (2006)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Goodwin, C. &amp; Brewin, P. E. &amp; Brickle, P." box="[406,661,333,359]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="1 - 48" refId="ref35020" refString="Goodwin, C., Brewin, P. E. &amp; Brickle, P. (2012) Sponge biodiversity of South Georgia island with descriptions of fifteen new species. Zootaxa, 3542, 1 - 48. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3542.1.1" type="journal article" year="2012">
Goodwin 
<emphasis box="[519,577,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
report smaller oxeas of 420–590 μm and 365–476 μm respectively, more similar to the range in our specimens, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Koltun, V. M." box="[703,863,369,396]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="6 - 133" refId="ref35597" refString="Koltun, V. M. (1964) Sponges of the Antarctic I. Tetraxonida and Cornacuspongida. In: Pavilovskii, E. P., Andriyashev, A. P. &amp; Ushakov, P. V. (Eds.), Biological reports of the Soviet Antarctic expedition (1955 - 1958). Vol. 2. Akademya Nauk SSSR, Moscow, Leningrad, pp. 6 - 133." type="book chapter" year="1964">Koltun (1964)</bibRefCitation>
also gives a wider size range (382–600 μm). 
<bibRefCitation author="Rios, P." pageId="23" pageNumber="484" refId="ref36627" refString="Rios, P. (2006) Esponjas del orden Poecilosclerida de las campanas espanolas de bentos Antartico. Unpublished PhD Thesis, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, 527 pp." type="book" year="2006">Rios (2006)</bibRefCitation>
reports two categories of acanthostyles but this division is not apparent in our specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,153,647]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,440,467]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is widely distributed in the Antarctic: Alexander I land (
<bibRefCitation author="Topsent, E." box="[1136,1294,441,467]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref37835" refString="Topsent, E. (1917) Spongiaires. In: Joubin, L. (Ed.), Deuxieme Expedition Antarctique Francaise (1908 - 1910) Commandee par le Dr. Jean Charcot. Sciences Physiques: Documents Scientifiques. Masson &amp; Cie, Paris, pp. 1 - 88." type="book chapter" year="1917">Topsent 1917</bibRefCitation>
), Wilheim II coast, Banzare coast, Wilkes Land, Victoria Land, Princess Astrid Coast (
<bibRefCitation author="Koltun, V. M." box="[968,1115,477,504]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="6 - 133" refId="ref35597" refString="Koltun, V. M. (1964) Sponges of the Antarctic I. Tetraxonida and Cornacuspongida. In: Pavilovskii, E. P., Andriyashev, A. P. &amp; Ushakov, P. V. (Eds.), Biological reports of the Soviet Antarctic expedition (1955 - 1958). Vol. 2. Akademya Nauk SSSR, Moscow, Leningrad, pp. 6 - 133." type="book chapter" year="1964">Koltun 1964</bibRefCitation>
), MacRobertson Coast (Kol- tun 1976), Weddell Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Barthel, D. &amp; Tendal, O. S. &amp; Panzer, K." box="[431,647,513,539]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="120 - 131" refId="ref33787" refString="Barthel, D., Tendal, O. S. &amp; Panzer, K. (1990) Ecology and taxonomy of sponges in the eastern Weddell Sea shelf and slope communities. Reports on polar research, 68, 120 - 131." type="journal article" year="1990">
Barthel 
<emphasis box="[523,580,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">et al.</emphasis>
1990
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gutt, J. &amp; Koltun, V. M." box="[659,892,512,539]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="227 - 234" refId="ref35072" refString="Gutt, J. &amp; Koltun, V. M. (1995) Sponges of the Lazarev and Weddell Sea, Antarctica: explanations for their patchy occurrence. Antarctic Science, 7, 227 - 234. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0954102095000320" type="journal article" year="1995">Gutt &amp; Koltun 1995</bibRefCitation>
), Ross Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Pansini, M. &amp; Calcinai, B. &amp; Cattaneo-Vietti, R. &amp; Sara, M." box="[1031,1248,513,539]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="67 - 100" refId="ref36291" refString="Pansini, M., Calcinai, B., Cattaneo-Vietti, R. &amp; Sara, M. (1994) Demosponges from Terra Nova Bay (Ross Sea, Antarctica): 1987 / 1988 and 1989 / 90. Programma Nazionale di Ricerche in Antartide, Expeditions. National Scientific Commission for Antarctica Oceanographic Campaign 1987 / 88 and 1989 / 90, 3, 67 - 100." type="journal article" year="1994">
Pansini 
<emphasis box="[1123,1180,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">et al.</emphasis>
1994
</bibRefCitation>
), South 
<collectingCountry name="Trinidad Island" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">Trinidad Island</collectingCountry>
and Bransfield Strait (
<bibRefCitation author="Rios, P." box="[473,593,549,576]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" refId="ref36627" refString="Rios, P. (2006) Esponjas del orden Poecilosclerida de las campanas espanolas de bentos Antartico. Unpublished PhD Thesis, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, 527 pp." type="book" year="2006">Rios 2006</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<collectingCountry box="[659,821,549,575]" name="South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">South Georgia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Goodwin, C. &amp; Brewin, P. E. &amp; Brickle, P." box="[835,1069,549,575]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="1 - 48" refId="ref35020" refString="Goodwin, C., Brewin, P. E. &amp; Brickle, P. (2012) Sponge biodiversity of South Georgia island with descriptions of fifteen new species. Zootaxa, 3542, 1 - 48. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3542.1.1" type="journal article" year="2012">
Goodwin 
<emphasis box="[948,1005,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
) from depths 
<quantity box="[1225,1348,549,575]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.9" metricValueMax="13.7" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" unit="m" value="690.0" valueMax="1370.0" valueMin="10.0">10–1370m</quantity>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Burton, M." pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="393 - 458" refId="ref34303" refString="Burton, M. (1929) British Antarctic (' Terra Nova') Expedition, 1910. Natural History Report. Porifera: Part II: Antarctic Sponges. Zoology, 6, 393 - 458." type="journal article" year="1929">Burton (1929)</bibRefCitation>
also erroneously reported it as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ridley and Dendy, 1886)" authorityName="Ridley and Dendy" authorityYear="1886" baseAuthorityName="Ridley and Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[737,1334,585,612]" class="Demospongiae" family="Dendoricellidae" genus="Pyloderma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="latrunculioides">
<emphasis box="[737,1036,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="484">Pyloderma latrunculioides</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ridley, S. O. &amp; Dendy, A." box="[1051,1325,585,612]" pageId="23" pageNumber="484" pagination="325 - 351" refId="ref36528" refString="Ridley, S. O. &amp; Dendy, A. (1886) Preliminary Report on the Monaxonida collected by H. M. S. &quot; Challenger. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 5, 18, 325 - 351. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222938609459982" type="journal article" year="1886">Ridley and Dendy, 1886</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the Antarctic but it is not clear which of his specimens are this species.
</paragraph>
